profiles = {
    "dense": {"icon":"■","badge":"■ DENSE","color":"#6C5CE7","title":"The Dense Writing Style","tagline":"Information-rich sentences. Layered meaning. Every word earns its place.","desc1":"Dense writers pack maximum meaning into every sentence. Their prose is rich with information, layered with subordinate clauses, and built to reward careful reading.","desc2":"This style features complex sentence structures, specialized vocabulary, and a high information-to-word ratio. Dense writing doesn't waste space.","traits":[("Sentence Length","Long"),("Information Density","Very High"),("Complexity","High"),("Vocabulary","Specialized")],"writers":["David Foster Wallace","Thomas Pynchon","Toni Morrison","William Faulkner","Virginia Woolf","James Joyce"],"writers_note":"These writers are known for prose that rewards re-reading. Each sentence contains multitudes.","example":"The negotiations, which had begun in earnest after the committee's third session—during which the delegates had finally agreed to a framework that, while imperfect, represented the first genuine compromise in decades—were now entering their most critical phase.","example_note":"Notice the layered clauses and the sheer amount of information compressed into a single sentence.","tips":["Your density is a gift for complex topics","Remember not every reader follows long sentences on first pass","Use paragraph breaks to give readers breathing room","In casual contexts, consider breaking complex sentences shorter","Your ability to compress ideas is rare"],"contexts":["Academic writing","Legal and policy documents","Literary fiction","Technical analysis","Philosophy and critical theory"],"related":[("minimal","MINIMAL"),("longform","LONGFORM"),("hedged","HEDGED")]},
    "interrogative": {"icon":"?","badge":"? INTERROGATIVE","color":"#FDCB6E","title":"The Interrogative Writing Style","tagline":"Questions that lead. Curiosity that drives. Writing that thinks out loud.","desc1":"Interrogative writers use questions as a primary rhetorical tool. Rather than declaring ideas, they invite readers into the thinking process.","desc2":"This style features frequent rhetorical questions, Socratic structures, and an exploratory tone that pulls readers forward.","traits":[("Question Frequency","High"),("Engagement Style","Dialogic"),("Tone","Exploratory"),("Reader Involvement","Very High")],"writers":["Malcolm Gladwell","Rebecca Solnit","Ta-Nehisi Coates","Roxane Gay","Michael Lewis","Mary Oliver"],"writers_note":"These writers use questions not as signs of uncertainty, but as tools for drawing readers deeper.","example":"But what happens when the system breaks down? When the safeguards we built turn out to be made of paper? Do we rebuild? Or do we finally ask the question we should have been asking from the start?","example_note":"Notice how each question builds on the last, creating momentum the reader can't resist.","tips":["Your questions create natural engagement","Balance questions with answers so readers don't feel lost","Rhetorical questions are powerful but overuse can feel manipulative","State your thesis clearly before exploring via questions","Your Socratic instinct is perfect for teaching"],"contexts":["Essays and opinion writing","Teaching and educational content","Persuasive writing","Investigative journalism","Blog posts and thought leadership"],"related":[("conversational","CONVERSATIONAL"),("hedged","HEDGED"),("assertive","ASSERTIVE")]},
    "hedged": {"icon":"~","badge":"~ HEDGED","color":"#00B894","title":"The Hedged Writing Style","tagline":"Careful qualification. Nuanced positions. Writing that respects complexity.","desc1":"Hedged writers build nuance into every claim. They use qualifiers, conditionals, and careful phrasing to acknowledge that most truths are partial.","desc2":"This style features frequent use of words like perhaps, it seems, arguably. Hedged writing isn't weak—it's intellectually honest.","traits":[("Qualifier Usage","High"),("Certainty Level","Moderate"),("Nuance","Very High"),("Precision","High")],"writers":["Susan Sontag","Zadie Smith","Adam Gopnik","Anne Lamott","Oliver Sacks","Marilynne Robinson"],"writers_note":"These writers demonstrate that hedging isn't hesitation—it's precision.","example":"It would be tempting to conclude that the policy failed entirely, though the reality is arguably more complex. In certain regions the outcomes appear to have been modestly positive, while elsewhere the results remain, at best, inconclusive.","example_note":"Notice the careful qualifications: tempting to conclude, arguably, appears, at best.","tips":["Your nuance is valuable—hedging is not weakness","In contexts demanding confidence, practice strategic directness","Your qualifications make you trustworthy","Balance hedging with clear thesis statements","Academic writing rewards your natural precision"],"contexts":["Academic and research writing","Policy analysis","Book reviews and criticism","Medical and scientific communication","Diplomatic communication"],"related":[("assertive","ASSERTIVE"),("interrogative","INTERROGATIVE"),("dense","DENSE")]},
    "longform": {"icon":"—","badge":"— LONGFORM","color":"#E17055","title":"The Longform Writing Style","tagline":"Extended thoughts. Patient development. Writing that takes its time.","desc1":"Longform writers develop ideas at length, building arguments through sustained attention and gradual revelation. Their sentences tend to be longer, their paragraphs more developed.","desc2":"This style favors thoroughness over brevity. Longform writers believe some ideas can't be compressed—they need room to breathe and unfold naturally.","traits":[("Sentence Length","Long"),("Development","Thorough"),("Pacing","Patient"),("Detail Level","High")],"writers":["John McPhee","Gay Talese","Rachel Carson","Robert Caro","Annie Dillard","Truman Capote"],"writers_note":"These writers prove that length is not the enemy of engagement.","example":"The river, which had been rising steadily since the early morning rains began their slow assault on the valley, was now approaching the old stone bridge that had stood since 1847, when the town's founders first laid its cornerstone.","example_note":"Notice the extended development, historical detail woven into description, the patient unfolding of context.","tips":["Your thoroughness is an asset for complex stories","Not every piece needs maximum length","Strong longform uses length purposefully","Pay attention to pacing and rhythm variation","Your patience with ideas is rare and valuable"],"contexts":["Narrative journalism","Memoir and autobiography","Historical writing","Environmental and science writing","Investigative reporting"],"related":[("dense","DENSE"),("minimal","MINIMAL"),("poetic","POETIC")]},
    "parallel": {"icon":"≡","badge":"≡ PARALLEL","color":"#0984E3","title":"The Parallel Writing Style","tagline":"Rhythmic structure. Balanced phrases. Writing that echoes itself.","desc1":"Parallel writers instinctively create balanced, rhythmic structures. They repeat grammatical patterns to build emphasis and give their prose a musical quality.","desc2":"This style features repeated syntactic structures, balanced clauses, and rhythmic patterning. It's a thinking style that organizes ideas through structure and repetition.","traits":[("Structural Repetition","Very High"),("Rhythm","Strong"),("Clarity","High"),("Rhetorical Power","Very High")],"writers":["Martin Luther King Jr.","Barack Obama","Charles Dickens","Abraham Lincoln","Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie","Winston Churchill"],"writers_note":"These writers used parallel structure to create some of the most memorable prose in history.","example":"We came to learn. We came to grow. We came to build something that would outlast our ambitions, outgrow our limitations, and outshine our doubts.","example_note":"Notice the repeated We came structure, the tripling of outlast/outgrow/outshine. Each repetition adds force.","tips":["Your natural rhythm makes your writing memorable","Vary your patterns to avoid becoming predictable","Parallel structure is powerful in speeches","In casual writing too much parallelism can feel formal","Your structural instinct helps readers follow complex arguments"],"contexts":["Speeches and public address","Persuasive essays","Marketing and brand copy","Motivational writing","Literary fiction"],"related":[("assertive","ASSERTIVE"),("poetic","POETIC"),("conversational","CONVERSATIONAL")]},
    "parenthetical": {"icon":"()","badge":"() PARENTHETICAL","color":"#E84393","title":"The Parenthetical Writing Style","tagline":"Asides and additions. Layered thought. Writing that thinks in brackets.","desc1":"Parenthetical writers constantly interrupt themselves—not from lack of focus, but from abundance of thought. Their prose is filled with asides that enrich the narrative.","desc2":"This style features frequent use of dashes, parentheses, and embedded clauses. It captures the natural movement of an active mind following interesting threads mid-sentence.","traits":[("Aside Frequency","Very High"),("Thought Layering","High"),("Conversational Feel","High"),("Digression","Controlled")],"writers":["David Sedaris","Nora Ephron","Dave Eggers","Zadie Smith","David Foster Wallace","Laurie Colwin"],"writers_note":"These writers turn parenthetical thinking into art. Their asides are where the real insight lives.","example":"The restaurant—which I'd been told (by someone whose taste I generally trust, though her enthusiasm for strip-mall sushi gives me pause) was the best in the neighborhood—turned out to be closed on Tuesdays.","example_note":"Notice the nested parentheticals, dashes creating space for asides, and how each digression adds personality.","tips":["Your asides are where your personality lives","In formal writing convert some parentheticals to separate sentences","Your natural style is perfect for essays and memoir","Readers love being inside an interesting mind","Watch for nesting too deep—two layers max"],"contexts":["Personal essays and memoir","Humor writing","Blog posts and newsletters","Creative nonfiction","Casual professional communication"],"related":[("conversational","CONVERSATIONAL"),("dense","DENSE"),("longform","LONGFORM")]}
}


template = open('/home/quirrely/quirrely.ca/profiles/assertive.html').read()

for key, p in profiles.items():
    c = p["color"]
    html = template
    # Replace meta/title
    html = html.replace('Assertive Writing Style', f'{key.title()} Writing Style')
    html = html.replace('ASSERTIVE', key.upper())
    html = html.replace('assertive writing style', f'{key} writing style')
    html = html.replace('assertive writer', f'{key} writer')
    html = html.replace('direct writing, confident writing, Hemingway style', f'{key} writing, writing voice, writing profile, Quirrely')
    html = html.replace('/profiles/assertive', f'/profiles/{key}')
    html = html.replace('#FF6B6B', c)
    html = html.replace('#ff8585', c + 'cc')
    # Replace badge
    html = html.replace('⚡ ASSERTIVE', p["badge"])
    html = html.replace('The Assertive Writing Style', p["title"])
    html = html.replace('Short sentences. High certainty. You say what you mean.', p["tagline"])
    # Replace description section
    html = html.replace('Assertive writers communicate with confidence and clarity. Their sentences are typically short and punchy, delivering ideas with conviction. There\'s little hedging or qualification—when an assertive writer makes a point, they commit to it fully.', p["desc1"])
    html = html.replace('This style is characterized by active voice, strong verbs, and minimal use of qualifiers like "maybe," "perhaps," or "I think." Assertive writing respects the reader\'s time by getting straight to the point.', p["desc2"])
    # Replace section headers
    html = html.replace('What is Assertive Writing?', f'What is {key.title()} Writing?')
    html = html.replace('Famous Assertive Writers', f'Famous {key.title()} Writers')
    html = html.replace('Example of Assertive Writing', f'Example of {key.title()} Writing')
    html = html.replace('Tips for Assertive Writers', f'Tips for {key.title()} Writers')
    html = html.replace('Best Contexts for Assertive Writing', f'Best Contexts for {key.title()} Writing')
    html = html.replace('Are You an Assertive Writer?', f'Are You a {key.title()} Writer?')
    html = html.replace('assertive writing voice', f'{key} writing voice')
    # Replace traits
    old_traits = html[html.find('<div class="traits-grid">'):html.find('</div>\n    </section>', html.find('traits-grid'))+len('</div>\n    </section>')]
    new_traits = '<div class="traits-grid">\n'
    for t in p["traits"]:
        new_traits += f'        <div class="trait"><div class="trait-label">{t[0]}</div><div class="trait-value">{t[1]}</div></div>\n'
    new_traits += '      </div>\n    </section>'
    html = html.replace(old_traits, new_traits)
    # Replace writers
    old_w_start = html.find('<div class="writers-list">')
    old_w_end = html.find('</div>', old_w_start) + 6
    new_w = '<div class="writers-list">\n'
    for w in p["writers"]:
        new_w += f'        <span class="writer-tag">{w}</span>\n'
    new_w += '      </div>'
    html = html[:old_w_start] + new_w + html[old_w_end:]
    html = html.replace('These writers are known for their direct, uncompromising prose. Hemingway\'s "iceberg theory" embodies assertive writing—say less, mean more.', p["writers_note"])
    # Replace example
    old_ex = '"The old man was thin and gaunt with deep wrinkles in the back of his neck. He was too old to fish alone. But today he would go out. He would catch the big fish. He would prove them wrong."'
    html = html.replace(old_ex, f'"{p["example"]}"')
    html = html.replace('Notice the short sentences. The declarative statements. No hedging. No "maybe" or "perhaps." Just clear, confident prose.', p["example_note"])
    # Replace tips
    old_tips = ['Your directness is a strength—don\'t dilute it with unnecessary qualifiers','When collaborating, remember that others may need more context','Short sentences have impact, but variety in length adds rhythm','Your confidence can inspire, but stay open to other perspectives','In formal contexts, a little hedging can show intellectual humility']
    for i, ot in enumerate(old_tips):
        if i < len(p["tips"]):
            html = html.replace(ot, p["tips"][i])
    # Replace contexts
    old_ctx = ['News and journalism','Executive communications','Marketing copy and calls to action','Technical documentation','Fiction with a spare, literary style']
    for i, oc in enumerate(old_ctx):
        if i < len(p["contexts"]):
            html = html.replace(oc, p["contexts"][i])
    # Replace related
    html = html.replace('If you\'re not assertive, you might be:', '')
    old_rel = html.find('<a href="/profiles/minimal" class="writer-tag">')
    if old_rel > 0:
        old_rel_end = html.find('</div>', old_rel) 
        new_rel = ''
        for r in p["related"]:
            new_rel += f'<a href="/profiles/{r[0]}" class="writer-tag">{r[1]}</a>\n        '
        html = html[:old_rel] + new_rel + html[old_rel_end:]
    filepath = f'/home/quirrely/quirrely.ca/profiles/{key}.html'
    with open(filepath, 'w') as f:
        f.write(html)
    print(f'Created {filepath}')
print('Done - 6 profiles created')
